        <name>37.3.3.4 The Poisson Process: Defective transistors</name>
        <questiontext>&lt;p class="HELM_exercise"&gt;Exercise&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;br&gt;Previous results indicate that \({@a@}\) in \(1000\) transistors are defective on average.
&lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ol class="HELM_parts"&gt;
    &lt;li&gt;Find the probability (to 4 decimal places) that there are \(4\) defective transistors in a batch of \(2000\): &lt;br&gt;\(\text{P}(\text{exactly 4}) = \) [[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]] [[feedback:prt1]]&lt;/li&gt;
    &lt;li&gt; What is the largest number, \(N\), of transistors that can be put in a box so that the probability of no defectives is at least \(\dfrac{1}{2}\)? &lt;br&gt;\(N = \) [[input:ans2]] [[validation:ans2]] [[feedback:prt2]]&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;</questiontext>
        <questiontextformat>1</questiontextformat>
        <generalfeedback>&lt;h4 class="HELM_solution"&gt;Solution&lt;/h4&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ol class="HELM_parts"&gt;
    &lt;li&gt;Let \(X\) be the random variable for the number of defective transistors, then \(X \sim \text{Poisson}(\lambda)\) where \(\lambda = \dfrac{{@a@}}{1000} \times 2000 = {@2*a@}\). The probability that there are going to be \(4\) defective transistors
        is then \[\text{P}(X=4) = \dfrac{{@2*a@}^4 e^{-{@2*a@}}}{4!} = {@ta1@} (\text{to 4 d.p.}).\]&lt;/li&gt;
    &lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
    &lt;li&gt;We see that on average there are going to be \(N \times \dfrac{{@a@}}{1000}\) defective transistors in a batch of \(N\), hence \(\lambda = \text{E}[X] = N\dfrac{{@a@}}{1000}\). To have no defective transistor in the box with probability at least \(\dfrac{1}{2}\)
        we must find the largest \(N\) such that: \[\begin{align*} \text{P}(X=0) &amp;amp;&amp;gt; \dfrac{1}{2}\\ e^{-\dfrac{N{@a@}}{1000}} \left(\dfrac{N{@a@}}{1000}\right)^0\dfrac{1}{0!} &amp;amp; &amp;gt; \dfrac{1}{2} \\ &amp;nbsp;e^{-\dfrac{N{@a@}}{1000}} &amp;amp; &amp;gt;
        \dfrac{1}{2}\\ -\dfrac{N{@a@}}{1000} &amp;amp; &amp;gt; -\ln(2) \\ \dfrac{N{@a@}}{1000} &amp;amp; &amp;lt; \ln(2) \\ N &amp;amp;&amp;lt; \dfrac{1000}{{@a@}}\ln(2) = {@displaydp(N_est,2)@} (\text{to 2 d.p.}).\end{align*}\] This means that the largest number of transistors
        to have in a batch to meet the requirements is \(N = {@ta2@}\).&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;</generalfeedback>
